"Pancost R.D., Steart D.S., Handley L., Collinson M.E., Hooker J.J., Scott A.C., Grassineau N.V., Glasspool I.J.","Increased terrestrial methane cycling at the Palaeocene-Eocene thermal maximum",2007,"Nature","449","7160",,"332","335",,,10.1038/nature06012,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34548835009&partnerID=40&md5=a503ed5f42360e0d62ccb9b59f2e7217","Bristol Biogeochemistry Research Centre, School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Cantock's Close, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Department of Geology, Royal Holloway University of London, Egham, Surrey TW20 0EX, United Kingdom; Palaeontology Department, Natural History Museum, Cromwell Road, London SW7 5BD, United Kingdom; Department of Geology, Field Museum, 1400 S. Lake Shore Drive, Chicago, IL 60605, United States","Pancost, R.D., Bristol Biogeochemistry Research Centre, School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Cantock's Close, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Steart, D.S., Department of Geology, Royal Holloway University of London, Egham, Surrey TW20 0EX, United Kingdom; Handley, L., Bristol Biogeochemistry Research Centre, School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Cantock's Close, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Collinson, M.E., Department of Geology, Royal Holloway University of London, Egham, Surrey TW20 0EX, United Kingdom; Hooker, J.J., Palaeontology Department, Natural History Museum, Cromwell Road, London SW7 5BD, United Kingdom; Scott, A.C., Department of Geology, Royal Holloway University of London, Egham, Surrey TW20 0EX, United Kingdom; Grassineau, N.V., Department of Geology, Royal Holloway University of London, Egham, Surrey TW20 0EX, United Kingdom; Glasspool, I.J., Department of Geology, Field Museum, 1400 S. Lake Shore Drive, Chicago, IL 60605, United States","The Palaeocene-Eocene thermal maximum (PETM), a period of intense, global warming about 55 million years ago, has been attributed to a rapid rise in greenhouse gas levels, with dissociation of methane hydrates being the most commonly invoked explanation. It has been suggested previously that high-latitude methane emissions from terrestrial environments could have enhanced the warming effect, but direct evidence for an increased methane flux from wetlands is lacking. The Cobham Lignite, a recently characterized expanded lacustrine/mire deposit in England, spans the onset of the PETM and therefore provides an opportunity to examine the biogeochemical response of wetland-type ecosystems at that time. Here we report the occurrence of hopanoids, biomarkers derived from bacteria, in the mire sediments from Cobham. We measure a decrease in the carbon isotope values of the hopanoids at the onset of the PETM interval, which suggests an increase in the methanotroph population. We propose that this reflects an increase in methane production potentially driven by changes to a warmer and wetter climate. Our data suggest that the release of methane from the terrestrial biosphere increased and possibly acted as a positive feedback mechanism to global warming. ©2007 Nature Publishing Group.",,"hopanoid; methane; bacterium; biomarker; carbon isotope; Eocene; feedback mechanism; global warming; greenhouse gas; Hypsithermal; lignite; mire; Paleocene; terrestrial ecosystem; wetland; air pollution; article; bacterium; ecosystem; environment; Eocene; greenhouse effect; human; methanotroph; Paleocene; priority journal; thermal analysis; United Kingdom; England; Eurasia; Europe; United Kingdom; Western Europe",,"methane, 74-82-8",,,,"Zachos, J.C., A transient rise in tropical sea surface temperature during the Paleocene-Eocene Thermal Maximum (2003) Science, 302, pp. 1551-1554; Dickens, G.R., Rethinking the global carbon cycle with a large, dynamic and microbially mediated gas hydrate capacitor (2003) Earth Planet. Sci. Lett, 213, pp. 169-183; Sloan, L.C., Walker, J.C.G., Moore, T.C., Rea, D.K., Zachos, J.C., Possible methane-induced polar warming in the early Eocene (1992) Nature, 357, pp. 320-322; Sloan, L.C., Pollard, D., Polar stratospheric clouds: A high latitude warming mechanism in an ancient greenhouse world (1998) Geophys. Res. Lett, 25, pp. 3517-3520; Collinson, M.E., Hooker, J.J., Gröcke, D.R., (2003) Causes and Consequences of Globally Warm Climates in the Early Paleogene, pp. 333-349. , eds Wing, S. L, Gingerich, P. D, Schmitz, B. & Thomas, B, Geol. Soc. Am. Special Paper 369, Boulder, Colorado; Kennett, J.P., Stott, L.D., Abrupt deep-sea warming, palaeoceanographic changes and benthic extinctions at the end of the Palaeocene (1991) Nature, 353, pp. 225-229; Bowen, G.J., Beerling, D.J., Koch, P.L., Zachos, J.C., Quattlebaum, T., A humid climate state during the Palaeocene/Eocene thermal maximum (2004) Nature, 432, pp. 495-499; Crouch, E.M., The Apectodinium acme and terrestrial discharge during the Paleocene-Eocene thermal maximum: New palynological, geochemical and calcareous nannoplankton observations at Tawanui, New Zealand (2003) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol, 194, pp. 387-403; Zachos, J., Pagani, M., Sloan, L., Thomas, E., Billups, K., Trends, rhythms, and aberrations in global climate 65Ma to present (2001) Science, 292, pp. 686-693; Collinson, M.E., Steart, D.C., Scott, A.C., Glasspool, I.J., Hooker, J.J., Episodic fire, run-off and deposition at the Palaeocene-Eocene boundary (2007) J. Geol. Soc. Lond, 164, pp. 87-97; Magioncalda, R., L'excursion isotopique du carbone organique (d13C) dans les paléoenvironnements continentaux de l'intervalle Paléocène/Eocène de Varengeville (Haute-Normandie) (2001) Bull. Soc. Geol. Fr, 172, pp. 349-358; Steurbaut, E., Palynology, palaeoenvironments, and organic carbon isotope evolution in lagoonal Paleocene-Eocene boundary settings in North Belgium (2003) GSA Spec. Pap, 369, pp. 291-317; Xie, S.C., Pancost, R.D., Yin, H.F., Wang, H.M., Evershed, R.P., Two episodes of microbial change coupled with Permo/Triassic faunal mass extinction (2005) Nature, 434, pp. 494-497; Eglinton, G., Hamilton, R.J